This instruction set is for creating a set of help documents in markdown format that describe canlab core tools. Format all documents so they will render well when used on the web at canlab.github.io.

1. Object methods
Create a markdown page in docs called Object_methods.md.  This will serve as an organizational page for the types of objects available and their methods.  This page will link to other pages, each an .md file, describing object methods for each object class.

In Object_methods.md:
- Briefly describe what objects and methods are ("things you can do with objects") and the major classes of objects.  Pull from documentation in major functions, including class constructors and online help docs at canlab.github.io, to create the description.

- Include a table of object classes with a brief description of what they are and links to pages describing each.

- Include links to the existing Walkthroughs and Tutorials pages on canlab.github.io and point to them in a visible way.

- For each object class page, create a markdown file called <class_name>_methods.md in docs/.  For example, for @fmri_data class, fmri_data_methods.md.  For each object class, first start with a description of what the object class is for, what kind of data it stores, and what kinds of  methods can be done with them in general. Keep this brief (about 2 paragraphs). Then provide a table of the properties of the object and a one-line description of what each property is. Keep this table compact. Then describe the methods in a table.

- Populate the description of methods as follows.
Look at all the methods and come up with a list of them organized into groups. Some suggested groups are below, but you can alter these if needed. Make a list of these areas and the functions belonging to each group, and save in fmri_data_methods.md.

Groups of methods:
- Basic Image math and operations
- Display and visualization
- Resampling and interpolation
- Statistics and machine learning
- Tables
- Annotation with spatial similarity
- Data extraction
- Quality control
- Misc utilities

If there is an existing markdown file in docs/, e.g., fmri_data_methods.md, default to the organization and assignment of methods to categories there, because it may be manually edited.

Interoperability and converting among object types. Create a page called recasting_objects.md. Here write an explanation of how to convert objects of one class to another. Link to this page in an appropriate place in Object_methods.md.

2. Interacting with neuroimaging atlases and patterns

Make a page called atlases_regions_and_patterns.md.  In this page, describe the types of atlases that are available and how to load them. Explain how Canlab Core uses neuroimaging atlases, parcellations, and multivariate signatures available on Github in https://github.com/canlab/Neuroimaging_Pattern_Masks.  For the atlases, Refer to load_atlas.m for a list of these atlases. For each atlas, try to find the original authoritative scientific paper and include a reference to it and a hyperlink to the paper on the publisher's site. Use information on
https://sites.google.com/dartmouth.edu/canlab-brainpatterns/home, and also search the web as needed. link to the page as well.

Describe how a number of named regions are available to use as masks from which to extract data or run other processes like region-level multivariate prediction, connectivity, or parcel-wise GLM analyses. For these named regions, refer to canlab_load_ROI.m for a list of regions and write a section with a table describing these.

4. Sample datasets

Make a page called sample_datasets.md.  Describe the built-in test datasets available with CanlabCore. Say most are in the Sample_datasets/ folder. Refer to and use material from this website, as well as the contents of CanlabCore:
https://canlab.github.io/_pages/canlab_help_2c_loading_datasets/canlab_help_2c_loading_datasets.html

Some datasets may be newer additions and not described in the website.
Describe load_image_set(), which includes a registry of datasets that users can access by name. Make a table that describes all the datasets in the registry in load_image_set. For each dataset, try to find the original authoritative scientific paper and include a reference to it and a hyperlink to the paper on the publisher's site. Pay attention to which involve group-level image data (the 'emotionreg' dataset in Wager_et_al_2008_Neuron_EmotionReg) and which are time series data (Pinel_sample_fMRI_time_series).

3. Description of toolbox subfolders

Make a page called toolbox_folders.md in docs/.  include a table that lists each folder in CanlabCore and describes the contents in 1-3 lines.

5. Editorial style for class and method descriptions

The following stylistic guidance should be applied when writing or revising class introductions, class-table descriptions in Object_methods.md, and per-class methods pages. These rules came out of editorial passes on the first round of pages and capture how class descriptions should read.

5a. Lead with purpose, not structure.

When describing an object class, start with what it is FOR (the user's reason to reach for it) before what fields it has. Prefer "complete analysis-ready package for fMRI / PET / contrast images, with metadata fields to mark image semantics" over "Holds .dat plus optional .X, .Y, covariates, and metadata." Listing fields is fine inside the properties table; the prose intro should answer "why would I use this object?"

5b. Use both-and framing for dual-natured objects.

When an object holds two related representations (e.g., atlas: both winner-take-all integer labels AND probabilistic maps; predictive_model: both setup variables AND fitted-model artifacts; statistic_image: both raw stats AND a .sig threshold state), say so explicitly with "both X and Y." Don't pick one half and bury the other in the property list.

5c. Be lifecycle-aware for stateful objects.

For objects whose properties evolve through stages (predictive_model has pre-fit setup vs. post-fit artifacts; brainpathway has region-level vs. node-level data; fmri_data with .removed_voxels / .removed_images), introduce the properties section with a brief paragraph distinguishing the stages. The properties table itself stays per-property; the framing paragraph above it explains what changes and when.

5d. Document multiple construction paths.

When an object can be built more than one way (e.g., fmridisplay can be built by canlab_results_fmridisplay or by invoking display methods like montage or surface on an image_vector), name the paths explicitly. Don't pick one and call it "the" constructor.

5e. Add domain framing where it helps.

For classes that exist because of a research design pattern, name the pattern. Example: canlab_dataset is "designed for two-level datasets (within-person, between-person) common in cognitive neuroscience." That single sentence does more than enumerating its methods. Use this for canlab_dataset, fmri_glm_design_matrix, brainpathway, and similar where the "why" is non-obvious from the field list.

5f. Curate the index table.

The class table in Object_methods.md is a curated front door, not an exhaustive enumeration. Legacy classes that users should not reach for first (fmri_mask_image is the example; many newer methods accept fmri_data or image_vector as a mask directly) belong on their own per-class page but should NOT appear in the Object_methods.md class table. Mention legacy classes only in the per-class pages and only with a "(legacy; use X instead)" note. Order the index table by how often a typical user encounters the class, not alphabetically.

5g. Property descriptions: name what it IS before what it DOES.

In properties tables, lead with the role / semantic label, then the mechanics. Prefer "Objective function; function handle computing accuracy from (Y, yfit)" over "Function handle computing accuracy from (Y, yfit)." For the mechanically-named property (accfun), the role label (objective function) is what helps the reader understand why it exists.

5h. When listing methods inline in prose, pick a small representative set.

For each class's intro paragraph, list 4-7 representative method names, not 12. The full method list is in the per-class page. The intro inline list is for orientation: it should show users what KIND of operations this class supports, not be a complete index. Example: "Most analysis methods (predict, regress, ica, searchlight, ttest, signtest) live here."

5i. Cross-link liberally between related pages.

Every per-class page should link to: (a) Object_methods.md as the parent index, (b) recasting_objects.md for conversions, (c) any related class page (e.g., fmri_data_methods.md links to image_vector_methods.md because most methods are inherited from there). The reading flow should be: index -> per-class -> related-class, never a dead end.
